b'From downsizing staff to navigating relief programs, businesses are being forced to make difficult financial decisions \xe2\x80\x94 more than usual. b'\xe2\x80\x9cI keep thinking of a March 16th date. I\xe2\x80\x99m thinking about that last day. b"\xe2\x80\x9cAt the end of the day, if we're not supposed to have these restaurants and they're to close, then that is what is in the cards for me. I'm scrappy, and if I need to go get a job at Domino's and deliver pizza, I'll do it. I'm not worried about my livelihood. I'm worried about making sure my employees are safe and healthy and have food, and I'm worried about setting an example for my daughters, who are looking to us for stability.\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x94Carrie Morey, owner of @callieshotlittlebiscuit

b'With almost 40 years of experience in the ceramics world between them, @mudfire owners Deanna and Daphne are committed to providing a studio space for artists to learn and further their craft. MudFire closed down in mid-March to keep its staff and members safe, but that hasn\xe2\x80\x99t stopped them from continuing to champion their community with socially-distanced date nights and a holiday sale to support their local makers.

Here\xe2\x80\x99s how you can support MudFire:

b'\xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m proud of the way we got to this point. It\xe2\x80\x99s the harder path \xe2\x80\x94 the more difficult path with a lot of stress \xe2\x80\x94 but it\xe2\x80\x99s more rewarding for me. You have real friends and real relationships with people. That matters.\xe2\x80\x9d

Just like how he built his pizza shop, Scarr has forged his own path in its marketing using a key organic ingredient \xe2\x80\x94 word of mouth buzz. He doesn\xe2\x80\x99t pay for influencer endorsements or positive PR, so anything you see or hear about @scarrspizza comes purely from happy customers. The ethos is simple: create a great slice of pizza and people will show up; create a community and they will come back.

Watch all 5 episodes of \xe2\x80\x9cI Made This\xe2\x80\x9d with Scarr\xe2\x80\x99s Pizza on YouTube at squ.re/imadethis.

b'\xe2\x80\x9cEvery business has to have a team. You can\xe2\x80\x99t have the same people with the same mentalities and the same strengths on one team \xe2\x80\x94 you\xe2\x80\x99re not going to get anywhere.\xe2\x80\x9d

Meagan left the stability of her 9-to-5 corporate job to join the family business with her husband, Scarr. As she focuses on building the @scarrspizza brand, her number one priority is nurturing the community, both with Scarr\xe2\x80\x99s Pizza customers and behind the counter with their employees.

b'\xe2\x80\x9cYou can\xe2\x80\x99t help others unless you help yourself first, and then you help people around you.\xe2\x80\x9d

New York City is home to hundreds of pizza shops, which means competition is served up on every corner. But Scarr and Emmett have made it, each carving out a slice of NYC\xe2\x80\x99s pizza space for themselves and supporting each other along the way. While @scarrspizza dishes out classic slices on the Lower East Side, @emmettsnyc specializes in Chicago-style deep dish in the heart of the West Village.\xc2\xa0

b'\xe2\x80\x9cEveryone thinks pizza by the slice is meant to be bad because it\xe2\x80\x99s cheaper. The reality is that it\xe2\x80\x99s not meant to be bad. If it\xe2\x80\x99s done well, with proper ingredients and proper processes, you have a nutritious meal. I wanted to do something different, something that could leave an impact.\xe2\x80\x9d

At @scarrspizza, the perfect slice is made under one rule: choose quality ingredients and don\xe2\x80\x99t cut corners. After watching the quality of pizza decline across New York City, Scarr committed himself to using only the finest organic ingredients and learning about the chemistry behind making the healthiest slice possible.\xc2\xa0

Watch all 5 episodes of \xe2\x80\x9cI Made This\xe2\x80\x9d with Scarr\xe2\x80\x99s Pizza on YouTube at squ.re/imadethis.

b'Square and Wakefield Research recently conducted a survey of U.S. small business owners around civic engagement and the upcoming presidential election.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9476% say they plan to give their employees time off to vote this Election Day.
\xe2\x80\x94Among small business owners giving employees time off to vote, 83% say they plan to give paid time off.
\xe2\x80\x9426% say they would be willing to make Election Day a company-wide holiday to encourage voting.
\xe2\x80\x9467% say it is their civic responsibility to provide their employees with educational resources to make their own informed voting decisions.\xc2\xa0\xc2\xa0
\xe2\x80\x9437% say the opportunity to make a difference in the community is the top benefit of giving employees time off to vote.
\xe2\xa0\x80
Read the full survey results at the link in our bio.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cI remember in 4th grade, a guy would volunteer and come in once a month to teach us about business. His name was George, and he would teach us about supply and demand and I just fell in love with it. I was like, \xe2\x80\x98This is what I want to do. I want to own a business.\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Before picking up his own pizza peel, Scarr was a student of New York\xe2\x80\x99s best pizzerias, including @emiliosballato, @artichokepizza, and @joespizzanyc. In 2016, he opened Scarr\xe2\x80\x99s Pizza (@scarrspizza), a slice shop on Manhattan\xe2\x80\x99s Lower East Side centered around organic ingredients and a community-first atmosphere.\xc2\xa0

b'When art school didn\xe2\x80\x99t work out, Hek (@hektattoo) pivoted to tattooing. He got an apprenticeship and averaged 80 hours a week with two jobs to make his dream reality. Today, he\xe2\x80\x99s one of five artists at @thetattoogallery. When he isn\xe2\x80\x99t tattooing, Hek sits on the Huntington Beach Homeless Task Force, where he makes recommendations to the city council on how to help its homeless population. Hek describes himself as a proud community member, a concerned citizen, and someone who just wants what\xe2\x80\x99s best for his neighborhood.\n\nFollow @chefroychoi around Los Angeles as he talks with independent business owners about what makes their city special. Watch all 5 episodes on YouTube at squ.re/mycity.'

b'@pot_la is a full-service ceramics studio owned and operated by artists of color in Echo Park. A Los Angeles native, POT founder Mandy has watched her city change and experience rapid gentrification over the last 10 years. She opened the studio as a way to make people of color feel prioritized and reclaim space for the neighborhood\xe2\x80\x99s residents. POT offers sliding scale payments, free classes, and accessibility to any member of a marginalized community who wants to learn the art of pottery.

Follow @chefroychoi around Los Angeles as he talks with independent business owners about what makes their city special. Watch all 5 episodes on YouTube at squ.re/mycity.

Note: this series was filmed in December 2019. All of the small businesses in these videos have since been severely affected by COVID-19. To contribute directly via Cash App: $KogiBBQ, $POTstudioLA, $Hektattoo, $ElysianBarbershop.'

b'In Rockaway Beach, a diverse group of women have joined forces to support each other and grow their community. Founded in early 2016, members of the @ladiesofbusinessrockawaybeach meet monthly and are, in part, responsible for a new business boom in Rockaway Beach.\n\nPhotography by @michellegroskopf as part of our Dreams series. To see more stories visit square.com/dreams.'

b'The Albuquerque International Balloon Fiesta is the largest hot air balloon event on the planet. The festival spans 9 days, attracting nearly one million spectators every year. Pilots come from all over the world to take part in \xe2\x80\x9cmass ascensions\xe2\x80\x9d of more than 500 balloons. One of them is 18-year-old Savannah Bradley. She\xe2\x80\x99s a fourth-generation balloon pilot, but her family legacy hasn\xe2\x80\x99t insulated her from the difficulty of being a young woman in a sport dominated by men.\n\n\xe2\x80\x9cBalloons\xe2\x80\x9d was directed by @egrolled. Photography by @chrisdthompson and @niicollaus. To see more stories, visit square.com/dreams.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cExit 12\xe2\x80\x9d tells the story of Roman Baca, an Iraq War veteran who turned to his classical dance training to cope with post-war depression and anxiety.

The film was directed by @mogorjestani and was acquired by @searchlightpics in 2019. It has been recognized by @sxsw, @clioawards, @vimeo, @thewebbyawards, @theatlantic, @tellyawards, and more. Watch on IGTV or by visiting square.com/dreams.

Photography by @justjac.'

b'Roman Baca, an Iraq War veteran, turned to his classical dance training to cope with post-war depression and anxiety. He is the founder of Exit12, a contemporary dance company and one of 2.5 million veteran-owned businesses in the United States. 

Veterans like Roman have a propensity for entrepreneurship; a 2011 SBA Office of Advocacy study reported that veterans are about 45% more likely to become entrepreneurs than people with no active-duty military experience.

\xe2\x80\x9cExit 12\xe2\x80\x9d was directed by @mogorjestani and was acquired by @searchlightpics in 2019. The film has been recognized by @sxsw, @clioawards, @vimeo, @thewebbyawards, @theatlantic, @tellyawards, and more. To see more stories, visit square.com/dreams.

Photography by @justjac.'

b'After Maryam\xe2\x80\x99s release from prison, she struggled to find housing or employment. She began selling secondhand goods out of a suitcase on a street corner in New Orleans. In just three years, she grew her business to a brick-and-mortar thrift store\xe2\x80\x94one that also provided housing and employment for other formerly-incarcerated women.

\xe2\x80\x9cSister Hearts\xe2\x80\x9d was directed by @mogorjestani as part of our Dreams series, and has been recognized by @cannes_lions, @tribeca, @clioawards, @vimeo, @thewebbyawards, @theatlantic, @tellyawards and more. Watch on IGTV, YouTube, or by visiting square.com/dreams.

Photography by @terenceb.'

b'Maryam Henderson-Uloho spent 13 years in prison, seven in solitary confinement. After her release she struggled to find housing or employment. She began selling secondhand goods out of a suitcase on a street corner in New Orleans. In just three years, she grew her business to a brick-and-mortar thrift store\xe2\x80\x94one that also provided housing and employment for other formerly-incarcerated women. She calls those women\xe2\x80\x94and her store\xe2\x80\x94Sister Hearts (@sisterhearts_thriftstore). 

\xe2\x80\x9cSister Hearts\xe2\x80\x9d was directed by @mogorjestani as part of our Dreams series, and has been recognized by @cannes_lions, @tribeca, @clioawards, @vimeo, @thewebbyawards, @theatlantic, @tellyawards and more. To see more stories, visit square.com/dreams.

Photography by @terenceb.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cLakota in America\xe2\x80\x9d is the story of the Cheyenne River Youth Project, which is working with Lakota\xe2\x80\x99s youth to create a stronger economic and cultural future \xe2\x80\x94 using their Lakota heritage to get there. The film was directed by @mogorjestani as part of our Dreams series, and has been recognized by @vimeo, @thewebbyawards, @mashable, @tulsaamericanfilmfest, and more. Watch on IGTV, YouTube, or by visiting square.com/dreams.\n\nPhotography by @terenceb.'

b'Genevieve Iron Lightning is a young Lakota dancer on the Cheyenne River Reservation, one of the poorest communities in the U.S. Unemployment, addiction, alcoholism, and suicide are all challenges for Lakota on the reservation.

b"\xe2\x80\x9cOur company offers food and grocery deliveries to people in the Atlanta area. Since this pandemic started, I always wanted to be in a position of trying to help the best way I can. I'm just helping to make sure that people are staying inside.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cIt's risky on my part, just to make sure that I'm keeping safe and making sure that I'm not being exposed. I'm always equipped with a mask and gloves and hand sanitizer. At the same time, it's still something that I enjoy. Just keeping in mind that I'm able to serve my community. Even if people don't use my service, I'm just trying to preach that we need to try to flatten this curve. This is definitely something that I take pride in.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Atlanta can support @phishodelivers by visiting phishodelivers.com to place an order."

b"\xe2\x80\x9cMy team is ready to go as soon as we can start seeing patients again. We're gonna be working overtime. We're gonna be staying late, working evenings and working weekends, to make up for all the appointments we've had to postpone. We just have to be flexible enough to adjust for that. We've been here since 2010, and we're an important part of our community, and we hope to continue to be so.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cThere's 11 of us total. One of the biggest worries I had for my team is that I provide health benefits for them, so I didn't want to lay them off, remove those benefits, and then they have to fight to get COBRA or some other insurance plan that's gonna be completely not affordable for them. So, I told them I would maintain paying for their health insurance through\xc2\xa0this entire ordeal, and that way when they come back, everything just goes back to the way it was. The last thing I wanted to do was take away someone's health benefits in a health crisis, and then they, god forbid, contract the virus and not be able to get treated.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI'm doing virtual consultations with patients. We schedule a Zoom meeting or a FaceTime and I help diagnose if they have a true condition or not. It becomes a little bit of a situation where we have to be mindful of our patient's health and well-being. We are constantly telling our patients to look at the connection between their oral health and their physical health. I just urge other clinicians and other medical practitioners to be patient and to be mindful of the federal and state orders that are put in front of you.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80

b'@reverieroasters is a coffee shop and roastery located in Wichita, Kansas. To continue serving their customers, they\xe2\x80\x99ve opened a temporary drive-thru for curbside pickup.\xe2\x81\xa3\n\xe2\x81\xa3\nWe partnered with the @specialtycoffeeassociation to dig into how sellers have pivoted to continue serving coffee to their communities, from curbside pickup to doorstep delivery of fresh roasted beans. Read the full report at squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cThere's a lot of confusion as to who can open or when it's right to open. In fact, we are now able to open to the public with seating, but we believe it's far too soon to do that, so we're choosing not to. We've always had online sales, but now we're adding pickup window order sales, and we're utilizing our roasting production facility as an easy handoff point for people who made preorders. We saw a huge transition from sales through our website. Since we've been reopening slowly, more and more staff are starting to come back, but still very limited numbers. We're still obviously looking at what changes we would have to make in order to reopen, based on what's going on in our community. That's going to weigh heavily on what we look like going forward. We had gradually gone out of business and so we're gradually coming back into business.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
We partnered with @specialtycoffeeassociation to dig into how sellers\xe2\x80\x94like Andrew of @reverieroasters\xe2\x80\x94have pivoted to continue serving coffee to their communities, from curbside pickup to doorstep delivery of fresh roasted beans.\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cPeople are completely understanding with modifications that look different, feel different from the way they're used to simply because of what's going on right now. Contactless payments are clearly okay, and most people are buying in advance. For customers that arrive for pickup, they understand when we say there's no cash. Going forward, though, it's going to be hard to determine what people will accept. I know that in the past, when we've had conversations in our part of the country about going cashless, two mindsets very quickly come to light. The cash tip in the jar is very much a symbolic gesture that quite frankly, people just enjoy doing. I see that kind of situation not really going away. I guess these are the kinds of questions I'm going to have to think about in the next two weeks, as we get closer to the next version of ourselves, whatever that looks like.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Support Andrew and @reverieroasters by visiting reverieroasters.com to order pickup or delivery.\xc2\xa0To read the full 2020 Square Coffee Report, visit squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio."

Read the full report at squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cSo last time we spoke, everything was changing rapidly. It was right on the precipice of us making the tough decision to close two of our locations. But since that time, we've had a chance to regroup. We were approved under the first round of the PPP loans\xe2\x80\x94that kind of catapulted us back\xe2\x80\x94but it's been incredibly difficult because this virus is cutting off the human interaction. We believe what makes coffee a central part of a community is that human interaction. People aren't just coming in for a cup of coffee. They're coming in to interact, and that's one of the big challenges we're trying to think through. How do we still get the nuances of a human interaction through an online, mobile ordering platform, no matter how good it is? There\xe2\x80\x99s something more to that than just a transaction. It's not about a dollar exchange. It's about something much deeper than that.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
We partnered with @specialtycoffeeassociation to dig into how sellers\xe2\x80\x94like Nicholas of @fostercoffeeco\xe2\x80\x94have pivoted to continue serving coffee to their communities, from curbside pickup to doorstep delivery of fresh roasted beans.\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cOur customers actually clued us in like, \xe2\x80\x98Hey, could you bring this to us?\xe2\x80\x99 Absolutely, let's do it, and we launched it in a week. Our eCommerce side of things has increased pretty substantially. With a drop in wholesale customers, we've seen almost a complete supplement of smaller individual retail bag purchases here and there that have filled that gap. When your customer is your central focus, they give you the ideas because you're there to serve them. If that forces us to pivot, then we're gonna pivot.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Support Nicholas and @fostercoffeeco by visiting fostercoffee.co to order carry-out or curbside pickup. To read the full 2020 Square Coffee Report, visit squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio."

b'@ritualcoffee is a San Francisco-based coffee and roastery company with six Bay Area locations. To continue serving their customers, they\xe2\x80\x99re offering order ahead pickup, home brew tools, and grocery-style essentials.\xe2\x81\xa3\n\xe2\x81\xa3\nWe partnered with the @specialtycoffeeassociation to dig into how sellers have pivoted to continue serving coffee to their communities, from curbside pickup to doorstep delivery of fresh roasted beans. Read the full report at squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cI've been in the coffee industry for over 20 years, but I've had to solve problems over the past two months that I've never thought about before. As so many of the things in life that we take for granted are stripped away, simple ones like coffee become even more important. It's just a different flow for us. We only have three of our six caf\xc3\xa9s open right now. We've got skeleton crews working in each caf\xc3\xa9. I used to think about how to get the line as tight as possible, and now I'm like, how do I keep people far apart? You know, just so many new problems.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
We partnered with @specialtycoffeeassociation to dig into how sellers\xe2\x80\x94like Eileen of @ritualcoffee\xe2\x80\x94have pivoted to continue serving coffee to their communities, from curbside pickup to doorstep delivery of fresh roasted beans.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cI was getting frantic calls from other small business owners asking, \xe2\x80\x98What can you sell right now?\xe2\x80\x99 It was partly born out of the idea of \xe2\x80\x98How do we become more essential, while also supporting other small businesses?\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d How do businesses reach the customers who want their products while the normal outlets are closed? The first grocery-type item we brought in was from our pastry vendor, who also makes bread, so we started small with additional loaves of bread. It is sort of against the spirit of shelter in place to go out for a latte, but if you can also pick up a gallon of milk, a loaf of bread, and hand sanitizer, then it\xe2\x80\x99s worth it.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cAlmost every day we sell somebody a coffee grinder, which just makes me so happy that even after this is over, people have the tools in their home to make great coffee. We're seeing things like that where people are taking more time to enjoy this Ritual.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Support Eileen and @ritualcoffee by visiting ritualroasters.com to order a coffee subscription or donate to the city\xe2\x80\x99s frontline healthcare workers. To read the full 2020 Square Coffee Report, visit squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio."

b'@thearrowpdx is a coffeehouse in the heart of Portland, Oregon. To continue serving their customers, they\xe2\x80\x99re offering online-only ordering and free delivery within a one mile radius of their shop.\xe2\x81\xa3\n\xe2\x81\xa3\nWe partnered with the @specialtycoffeeassociation to dig into how sellers have pivoted to continue serving coffee to their communities, from curbside pickup to doorstep delivery of fresh roasted beans. Read the full report at squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cI remember the last day our cafe\xcc\x81 was open, we just said, \xe2\x80\x98All right, are we gonna fight for this, or are we gonna just go home?\xe2\x80\x99 And almost everyone said they're willing to stick it out. I have been working 15-hour days since the beginning of March and I'm tired.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
We partnered with @specialtycoffeeassociation to dig into how sellers\xe2\x80\x94like Erica of @thearrowpdx\xe2\x80\x94have pivoted to continue serving coffee to their communities, from curbside pickup to doorstep delivery of fresh roasted beans.
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cWe've lost about 15% of our gross sales, but we just feel the freedom now to innovate and do whatever we want. I've been able to hire some professional chefs who've gotten laid off from their super fancy kitchen jobs, and they're so up for doing fun things that we've never done before. We did a burger day where we actually made burgers and sold them out of our coffee shop. We\xe2\x80\x99ve done French toast, biscuits and gravy, and things that we've never thought about doing before. I am totally making this up as I go along, and every week I just decide \xe2\x80\x98What can we do this week to raise sales? What can we do to connect with our customers without actually being near them?\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cI ordered a drive through speaker box and it comes with a mic. You talk out and they talk in. I found this retail sign holder, ordered signs to put into it, and attached the speaker box to that. We take it in and out every day. This needs to be organized, this needs to be fast. We are losing a huge convenience factor right now. Yes, we are still a destination, but a destination isn\xe2\x80\x99t fun if it isn\xe2\x80\x99t an experience. So, we are still creating that customer experience, but in a different way.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Support Erica and @thearrowpdx by visiting arrowcoffeehouse.com to order curbside pickup or delivery. To read the full 2020 Square Coffee Report, visit squ.re/coffeereport or click the link in our bio."

While a lot has changed in the past few months, passion for great coffee persists and so does the commitment to serving it. b"\xe2\x80\x9cFour months ago we moved to double our location size and staff which was really going great after we'd been open for five years now. And then COVID hit all of us. Obviously we had to pivot and change real quick which we've been doing really on a daily basis for the last month.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cI did have a very strong feeling that I didn't want to close my doors. I needed to still serve the community in some way. When we started doing the meals for the healthcare workers, it felt like we had a real purpose. We have delivered a little over 2,000 meals, and we did nine different hospitals. My most vulnerable staff was able to stay employed and we were also now making nice, quality meals for the healthcare workers that are obviously the heroes in these times. b'We think it\xe2\x80\x99s important to be fully transparent in how our payment processing fees are distributed. When a customer spends money with your business, Square only keeps a fraction of the fees, with most going right back into your business.
\xe2\xa0\x80
To process a sale, there are several types of set fees within a transaction. These are not set by Square, but by cardholder banks and card networks. They are included as part of our processing fee. This visual breaks down these payment details, showing you where fees from each sale go.
\xe2\xa0\x80
Right now, card-not-present (CNP) payments are especially important. There are multiple types of CNP payments, and Square pays more for these transactions. The fee increase for these payments go directly to the customer\xe2\x80\x99s card issuing bank to help mitigate the risk of fraud and protect your business.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94When you manually key in your customer\xe2\x80\x99s card details or use a card on file, the fee is 3.5% + 15\xc2\xa2.
\xe2\x80\x94When a customer makes a purchase through your Square Online Store, Square Online Checkout, eCommerce API, or pays an invoice online, the fee is 2.9% + 30\xc2\xa2.
\xe2\xa0\x80
Please visit squ.re/feebreakdown for more information. Link in bio.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s not often that a family owned-and-operated business is successful, let alone a woman owned-and-operated business. We have our ups and downs, but that comes with the territory. Being in this space, it makes other women think \xe2\x80\x98We can do this too.\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Meet Denise and Crystal, the mother-daughter team leading Yo\xe2\x80\x99 Mama\xe2\x80\x99s (@yomamasmeals) in Birmingham, AL. After more than 30 years in the corporate world, Denise retired and started cooking for her church and at family reunions.\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cI always wanted to own a restaurant. I spent that time learning how to handle groups of people, and decided to step out and try it,\xe2\x80\x9d Denise said.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Denise\xe2\x80\x99s daughter Crystal offered to help with the marketing side of things. Yo\xe2\x80\x99 Mama\xe2\x80\x99s opened its doors to a steady stream of customers in 2014.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cShe\xe2\x80\x99s good with people, and I\xe2\x80\x99m good with food, so God has totally blessed us,\xe2\x80\x9d Crystal said.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Yo\xe2\x80\x99 Mama\xe2\x80\x99s menu is faithful southern fare \xe2\x80\x94 chicken & waffles, shrimp & grits, mac & cheese \xe2\x80\x94 but with a twist: every single dish on the menu can be made gluten-free, and meals are made fresh to order.
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cI wanted to have a restaurant where we only have a few things on the menu, but every age group is covered, so a family could come in and find something for everyone.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Denise and Crystal\xe2\x80\x99s first priority is serving the Birmingham community. They recently catered for @rhmcalabama and made Thanksgiving dinner for the city\xe2\x80\x99s homeless community three years running. Yo\xe2\x80\x99 Mama\xe2\x80\x99s also recently hosted @pete.buttigieg when he was in town. Whoever they\xe2\x80\x99re serving, they make it personal \xe2\x80\x94 tablecloths, flowers, and the same great food they feed their own families.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cWhat makes us special? Yo\xe2\x80\x99 Mama\xe2\x80\x99s is like you\xe2\x80\x99re going home.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Yo\xe2\x80\x99 Mama\xe2\x80\x99s supports @triumphservices, which provides independent living skills, employment, and more for individuals with developmental disabilities. Click the link in our bio to learn more or donate.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3

b'\xe2\x80\x9cThere\xe2\x80\x99s no better time than right now for women in business. My grandmother said she never could have fathomed doing what I\xe2\x80\x99m doing now when she was my age. Maybe call it naive, but I never thought I couldn\xe2\x80\x99t do it.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Meet Laura Lemon, owner of @lemon_laine, a colorful natural beauty and wellness shop in East Nashville, TN. The space is bright and airy; sunbeams stream through large windows and reflect off curated rows of glass bottles bearing some of the biggest names in the natural beauty world. Laura wanted the store\xe2\x80\x99s interior to look like \xe2\x80\x9cyour bathroom medicine cabinet,\xe2\x80\x9d so customers would feel at ease browsing new products.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cLemon Laine is about making beauty feel fun and comfortable again by creating a space that feels like home.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
For Laura, Nashville was the perfect place to put down roots. The city\xe2\x80\x99s network of women entrepreneurs has been particularly supportive of Lemon Laine.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cBeing a transplant from the west coast and only knowing one person in Nashville before I opened our doors, I was blown away by the support from the beginning, thanks in large part to other women business owners that helped spread the word about us. Nashville really wants to see small businesses succeed. You know your neighbor here, and they come out to support because they want to build a community that leans on each other and is around for the long-haul. The immediate and overwhelming local response of volunteers and donations for the tornado relief has made it even more apparent what community truly means here in Nashville. There\xe2\x80\x99s really no place like it.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Laura supports @communityfoundationmidtn, which has set up an emergency response fund for relief efforts in the wake of Nashville\xe2\x80\x99s recent tornadoes. Click the link in our bio to learn more or donate.\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Lemon Laine is also holding weekly Safe Space Monday events from 6-8pm. They are designed to provide emotional and mental health support to the Nashville community as it recovers from the tornadoes.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3

b'\xe2\x80\x9cAs a woman of color, it\xe2\x80\x99s really important for me to support other women of color who start their own businesses. It\xe2\x80\x99s refreshing to see someone who looks like you, whose story you can identify with.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Meet Samantha Shih, owner of @9Tailors in Boston, MA.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cI just don't have the proportions of a 5'10", size two model. I would have to either get things tailored or resign myself to the fact that I was going to be as presentable as possible, but it wasn't going to feel perfect.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
While on a trip to visit family in China, Samantha met skilled tailors who were able to take the clothes she wanted to wear and alter them to fit perfectly. When she couldn\xe2\x80\x99t think of a place she could go to in Boston for the same service, she decided to build it herself. 9Tailors offers menswear, women\xe2\x80\x99s suits, and custom attire for the LGBTQ+ community.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cClients come in and share stories about struggling to find clothes that don\xe2\x80\x99t make them feel awkward or very public shopping experiences where they have to explain to someone what\xe2\x80\x99s happening. Our showroom is private, all 1-on-1. Every year that I'm in this business, I learn more about my customers and communities that have been ignored by traditional brands. I\xe2\x80\x99m trying to make clothing that fits everybody.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
9Tailors customers might have different items in mind when stopping in, but they\xe2\x80\x99re all looking for the same thing \xe2\x80\x94 clothes they feel confident in.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cWhen people leave the shop, they feel empowered \xe2\x80\x94 smarter about their own style and confident in being able to dress themselves the way they want,\xe2\x80\x9d said Samantha. \xe2\x80\x9cGQ once named Boston the worst-dressed city in America. I feel like I\xe2\x80\x99m helping to combat that stigma.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
9Tailors supports @mccourtytwins Tackle Sickle Cell Foundation in their fight against sickle cell disease. Click the link in our bio to learn more or donate.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Photography by Lauren O\xe2\x80\x99Neil (@lauoneil), a Boston-based photographer, art director, and graphic designer. Her work has been featured by @nike, @apple, @puma, @grillospickles and more.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cThere was a point where I was just like, \xe2\x80\x98Is this really worth it? Am I kidding myself?\xe2\x80\x99 But I made it through, and whenever I get discouraged now, I think about that.\xe2\x80\x9d\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Samantha Heligman is the sole artist behind Settle Ceramics (@settle_ceramics), her studio in Austin, Texas, where she hand-throws pieces meant to last forever. Her journey began in 2008, when she sat at the pottery wheel for her first ceramics class. That one class spun into a passion that caught the eye of @keithkreeger, a renowned artist in Austin\xe2\x80\x99s ceramics scene, who brought her onto his team.\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cThere's a huge ceramics community in Austin,\xe2\x80\x9d said Samantha. \xe2\x80\x9cYou get excited about their work and they get excited about yours. Most potters I\xe2\x80\x99ve met here want to help each other out.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Samantha was learning every day from Keith, but it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t always easy.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cWhen I first moved here I was basically working three jobs. I was doing massage therapy six days a week and working for Keith four days a week. Then I'd try and find time to make my own work, so I'd have 14 to 16 hour days sometimes. I\xe2\x80\x99m so busy with Settle now that when I look back, it makes those long hours worth it.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
When Samantha sits down at her wheel, she thinks of what she would use and cherish in her own home. That seems to have struck a chord with her community \xe2\x80\x94 @barleyswine, @elizabethstreetcafe, and other popular Austin restaurants are all customers of Settle Ceramics.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s such a thrill to me to see my plates and know people are eating off of them. I love that my community wants to buy my work and have it as part of the experience at their restaurants, and I get customers from that exposure. It\xe2\x80\x99s important to participate in and support your local economy in that way \xe2\x80\x94 both giving and receiving.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
Samantha supports Austin Pets Alive! (@austinpetsalive), a shelter that rescues at-risk animals and has made Austin the largest no kill city in the country. Click the link in our bio to learn more or donate.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x94\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3

b"\xe2\x80\x9cI want to do what I love, but at the same time I do want to live off doing what I love.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
This is Oaklin Mixon, owner of GoodBoy Clothing (@goodboyclothes) in Flint, Michigan. He created GoodBoy in 2014, starting with high quality t-shirts. The brand has expanded since then, and now offers apparel and accessories for men, women, and children. GoodBoy collaborates with different artists, designers, and seamstresses to provide an outlet for original ideas and unique collaboration. For Oaklin, community is the driving force behind GoodBoy\xe2\x80\x99s purpose.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI think art has a way of shaping culture and informing people, while also solving problems,\xe2\x80\x9d said Oaklin. \xe2\x80\x9cI think it's very important to bring people together. That's one of our core values. I wanted a brand that could represent anyone contributing to their community, shaping culture in a way that makes their city more wholesome.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Oaklin is one of the many businesses owners and entrepreneurs helping rebuild Downtown Flint. Click the link in our bio to watch our short film, Forged in Flint.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94

b'\xe2\x80\x9cIn my neighborhood, when you\xe2\x80\x99re born with this skin color it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t easy to get the opportunities like a white person would.\xe2\x80\x9d

b"\xe2\x80\x9cBlack History Month is a celebration of the contributions and accomplishments of black people to this country. We need to gain a greater understanding and appreciation for the traditions rooted in that rich history.\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x94Lauren Stovall, marketing director, @hotsamsdetroit
\xe2\xa0\x80
Hot Sam\xe2\x80\x99s, the oldest clothing store in Downtown Detroit, recently celebrated its 99th anniversary. Lauren\xe2\x80\x99s father, Tony, has been the CEO of Hot Sam\xe2\x80\x99s since he took over as owner in 1994. Before that, he was the shop\xe2\x80\x99s top salesman, and has been part of the Hot Sam\xe2\x80\x99s family since 1974.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s challenging to sustain a business in an ever-changing economy,\xe2\x80\x9d said Lauren. \xe2\x80\x9cWe have already survived a depression and a recession, and we are thriving today. We can thank the city of Detroit for that.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
The store has a rich history spanning multiple generations, giving the brand a unique identity in the competitive and ever-changing city of Detroit. Hot Sam\xe2\x80\x99s has served its community with quality clothing for nearly 100 years, dressing every Detroit mayor since 1921 and recording artists like Marvin Gaye, The Temptations, and The Four Tops. Lauren\xe2\x80\x99s job is to keep growing the business, and she says the future is bright.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cOur brand tells the story of who we are and why we are here. It stretches beyond the clothing and the doors of the store, reaching into the homes in our community. Hot Sam's is an indigenous business of Detroit. We are stewards of the community, we are leaders of the community, and we are part of the history and legacy of our community.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Visit @hotsamsdetroit at 127 Monroe Ave. in Downtown Detroit."

b"Founded in 2015 by Carla Williams, Material Life is a retail concept shop dedicated to gathering, promoting, archiving, and making accessible the complexity of black life and history through photography, fashion, books, fine art, artists' edition, and vintage collectibles, with a particular emphasis on African American history.
\xe2\xa0\x80
An artist all her life, Carla\xe2\x80\x99s love for the community in which she lives and serves is at the forefront of what drives her.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI wanted to start a retail shop that supported local art here in New Orleans,\xe2\x80\x9d said Carla. \xe2\x80\x9cWe have the absolute best people, so there was no plan B. Having a plan B means you\xe2\x80\x99re setting yourself up to fail.\xe2\x80\x9d"

b"\xe2\x80\x9cBlack women inspire me. Statistically, we have so few resources in this country and also statistically do the most with them.\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x94Carla Williams, owner of Material Life (@materiallife) in New Orleans, LA
\xe2\xa0\x80
These entrepreneurs make up a collective at the Contemporary Arts Center (@cacnola) in New Orleans\xe2\x80\x99 Central Business District. From left to right: Kirby Jones of La Vie En Rose Cafe (@lavieenrosecafenola); Adriane Butler of LaSalle & Jackson (@lasalleandjackson); Carla Williams and Chipo @kandake of Material Life.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cWe are three independent businesses,\xe2\x80\x9d said Carla. \xe2\x80\x9cThe space has always had a coffee bar and a retail space, so I reached out to Adriane because I love her products. She makes beautiful wax print clothing here in New Orleans and it was a perfect tie in for the shop. Then I brought in Kirby Jones, who owns La Vie En Rose Cafe. She had been doing different popups and installations around town. It was a great opportunity to partner with businesses that could all represent themselves under one roof.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80

b'\xe2\x80\x9cCoffee comes from Africa \xe2\x80\x94 that\xe2\x80\x99s where the first coffee was grown \xe2\x80\x94 but you don\xe2\x80\x99t see a lot of people of color in the coffee industry.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Meet the Konte family, founders of @redbaycoffee. Keba Konte dipped his toe into the specialty coffee industry in 2014, roasting coffee in Whirley Pops \xe2\x80\x94 popcorn makers \xe2\x80\x94 that he found at thrift stores. From his garden shed, he built something he describes as \xe2\x80\x9cbeautiful.\xe2\x80\x9d Red Bay Coffee has grown into three Bay Area cafes, a roastery in Oakland\xe2\x80\x99s Fruitvale district, and a location opening soon in Los Angeles.\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
For the Konte family, this isn\xe2\x80\x99t just about making a good cup of coffee \xe2\x80\x94 it\xe2\x80\x99s about empowering their local community and coffee suppliers through economic opportunity. Red Bay is focused on making the speciality coffee industry a more inclusive space for everyone.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cHiring people and creating jobs is our North Star,\xe2\x80\x9d says Jessica, Keba\xe2\x80\x99s daughter. \xe2\x80\x9cWe hire formerly incarcerated women and young folks coming out of the foster system. We hire women in places of leadership, especially black women, whose families originate from coffee-producing countries.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\x81\xa3
Oakland is special to Keba and his family. They were priced out of San Francisco in the 1990s and moved to Oakland with the intention of building something that would help their community thrive. Red Bay\xe2\x80\x99s ethos is rooted in community, in building each other up, and in helping the city\xe2\x80\x99s entrepreneurs and makers succeed.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cTap into what your community has to offer, whether it\xe2\x80\x99s startup capital or space. Use the kitchen at church during the week when it\xe2\x80\x99s available. Really seek out the resources in your community, because there are more than you think.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'All eyes on brow lamination, which is exploding across the U.S. :eyes:\n\xe2\xa0\x80\n\xe2\x80\x9cAffordable brow maintenance has led consumers to turn to brow lamination,\xe2\x80\x9d said Felipe Chacon, chief economist at Square. \xe2\x80\x9cWhile the average price point is about $70, that is still 6x\xc2\xa0*less*\xc2\xa0than its more permanent counterpart, microblading. While we see brow lamination bookings increasing more than 3,100% over the last 5 months alone, it\xe2\x80\x99s opened up the same brow look to consumers who were previously priced out.\xe2\x80\x9d'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cBarack was a regular. But once he became a Senator, he turned into a phenomenon. I remember he came in when he was on the campaign trail. He sat down in the chair, and within 10 minutes there was a crowd of people outside. He was a rock star. It was crazy.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Ishmael Coye is the owner of Hyde Park Barbershop (@hphsbarbers) on Chicago\xe2\x80\x99s South Side. The barbershop is one of the oldest businesses in Hyde Park, and has been a neighborhood staple on East 53rd for nearly 100 years, with athletes, celebrities, and even presidents coming through. The shop is famously known as Barack Obama\xe2\x80\x99s barbershop.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cThe barbershop has been an important part of Hyde Park since 1927,\xe2\x80\x9d said Ishmael. \xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s a place people can feel safe. It\xe2\x80\x99s a place they can be proud of. It has helped create pride in our community.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
There\xe2\x80\x99s a certain nostalgia often carried by old school barbershops, and Ishmael\xe2\x80\x99s has that in spades. The shop is lined with barber stations, complemented by traditional oversized leather chairs. The subtle but unmistakable aroma of Pinaud aftershave fills the air. And the clippers quietly hum under the banter between barbers and their regulars as they discuss the topics of the day.

Ishmael started cutting hair for neighbors, classmates, and family when he was in 7th grade. By 14, his reputation as a barber in the neighborhood was growing. He started working at Hyde Park Barbershop after getting his barber license, and eventually took over the shop in 2002.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cBarbershops are special, and this one has been special to me for most of my life.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80
Ishmael supports The Night Ministry (@thenightministry), a nonprofit providing housing, health care, and social services to people who struggle with homelessness, poverty, and loneliness throughout Chicago. Click the link in our bio to learn more or donate.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80
Photography by Lawrence Agyei (@lawrenceagyei), a Chicago-based portrait photographer from Ghana. His work has been featured by @thefader, @apple, @vsco, @newyorkermag, and more.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cWhen I was in prison, I met a lot of wonderful women. Those women were with me when I was lonely, when I was hurting, when I was frustrated. Those women gave me comfort and I call those women my Sister Hearts.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Maryam Henderson-Uloho is the founder and owner of Sister Hearts thrift store (@sisterhearts_thriftstore) in Arabi, Louisiana.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cSister Hearts is a thrift store and a housing facility for ex-offenders to transition back into society. It\xe2\x80\x99s a bridge from incarceration to society. Because prison doesn\xe2\x80\x99t allow inmates to transition, they just release them. It takes time to adjust back to society. When I got out, they wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t allow me to open a bank account. I could not rent an apartment. When you would tell anybody that you\xe2\x80\x99ve been to prison, you\xe2\x80\x99re not gonna be able to work. So I had to start my own business.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80
Visit square.com/dreams or click the link in our bio to watch Sister Hearts, our short film about Maryam\xe2\x80\x99s story. It has been honored by @thewebbyawards, @clioawards, @vimeo, @cannes_lions, and more.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cWho inspires me? Any black woman who\xe2\x80\x99s ever done anything.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Naj Austin is the founder and CEO of Ethel\xe2\x80\x99s Club (@ethelsclub), a social and wellness club celebrating people of color. This is Naj in her own words.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cBeing a black woman and building a business specifically for people of color forces me to work differently. I don't have the luxury of failing upwards. The stakes are just higher for us. I'm trying to create more space for other black women to come up while knocking down the brick walls in front of me.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cWhen I first started pitching, I was asked how often people of color feel uncomfortable. I'm like, \xe2\x80\x98Well, a lot. All of the time. Do you understand how rules and laws have been made in this country?\xe2\x80\x99 That\xe2\x80\x99s when I realized I had to educate white people about what it means to live as a person of color before I can even pitch my company. How can I sit in a meeting and explain how systemic racism works?\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI'm building something that makes people feel better. When they walk in, you see their shoulders drop. They know no one's going to question why they're here. They know they're going to be treated with the respect they deserve. They see a reflection of who they are and their values. We had a member who once told me \xe2\x80\x98When I walk into Ethel\xe2\x80\x99s Club I feel like I\xe2\x80\x99m at church on Sunday\xe2\x80\x99 and I think about that all the time.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cThere are very few black women entrepreneurs raising venture capital. Very few who are *able* to raise venture capital. So every time you pass a hurdle, it feels like success, but it also feels like demise is always right around the corner. It\xe2\x80\x99s the pressure of perfection. There's no room for error. There's no room for mistakes.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80
Ethel\xe2\x80\x99s Club, named for Naj\xe2\x80\x99s grandmother, is backed by investors and advisors like @roxanegay74, @hannibalburess, and @alexia. Their Brooklyn space has a boutique with a rotating selection of apparel and goods designed by artisans of color. Visit shop.ethelsclub.com or click the link in our bio to shop Ethel\xe2\x80\x99s Club.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80

b'\xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re not doing this to build the business and sell it. We want to create generational wealth so 30 years from now our children can inherit and run the business.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\x81\xa3
Meet Bilal and Rafia, bakers-in-chief of Delightful Foods (@delightfulfoodsbakery), specializing in vegan desserts. They\xe2\x80\x99ll be selling at @oakfirstfridays tonight in Koreatown.\xc2\xa0\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3
Bilal started out as a salesman in the 1970s, selling the confections of another baker. But his own taste for baking made him curious about being on the other side of the business, where he could dream up recipes of his own. Bilal\xe2\x80\x99s first creation was a vegan cookie, which he dedicated to perfecting over the next 24 years.\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cA long time ago, vegan meant it didn\xe2\x80\x99t taste good. I proved that I can make a vegan cookie that tastes good.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
8 years ago, everything changed. Bilal\xe2\x80\x99s wife, Rafia, emigrated from Ghana and joined him in Oakland. Rafia challenged him to get creative and branch out into pies. She brought the pies to farmers markets and other community events, spreading the word about their desserts under a new name \xe2\x80\x94 Delightful Foods. Today, all of their pies are made in a small commercial kitchen in East Oakland, but a place of their own is the goal.\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x81\xa3\xe2\x81\xa3
\xe2\x80\x9cI really want to have my own place one day. That\xe2\x80\x99s my dream. My husband supports me, we just don\xe2\x80\x99t have what it takes right now: money,\xe2\x80\x9d says Rafia.\xe2\x81\xa3'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cI was a young black woman coming out of prison as a single mom. Society would say the odds were stacked against me, but it\xe2\x80\x99s actually what I used to push myself forward. Those aren\xe2\x80\x99t setbacks to me. That\xe2\x80\x99s a comeback.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Keysa Smith (@chef_ksmith) opened Spectacular Spudz \xe2\x80\x94 a baked potato shop modeled after a restaurant from her childhood called the Potato Patch \xe2\x80\x94 as a nod to the glory days of her hometown of Flint, Michigan.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI started this business with $10 in my pocket,\xe2\x80\x9d said Keysa. \xe2\x80\x9cI carried all the equipment by myself. Nobody believed that I could do it, and I think that makes me pretty relatable. I\xe2\x80\x99m relatable to the struggling college student. I\xe2\x80\x99m relatable to the guy coming out of the hood. I\xe2\x80\x99m relatable to the single parent. I\xe2\x80\x99m relatable to a lot of people. Hopefully seeing me will inspire others. If I can do it, you can too. I\xe2\x80\x99m living proof.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Keysa is one of the many businesses owners and entrepreneurs rebuilding Downtown Flint. Click the link in our bio to watch our short film, Forged in Flint.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80
Photograph by Benjamin Heath (@benjaminheath), a San Francisco-based lifestyle photographer from Indiana. Ben has been featured by @water, @nike, @natgeo, and more. You can view more of his work at benjaminheath.net.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cI didn't see black business owners in my neighborhood growing up, so it's really important for me to do what I'm doing. The more we can see ourselves out in the world, the more it inspires other people to know that something like this is possible.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
This is Maurice. He owns Bloom & Plume Coffee, a cafe he opened right next to his flower studio in Los Angeles\xe2\x80\x99 Historic Filipinotown. Maurice spent years putting his Fine Arts degree to work doing window design, retail, and commercials. He also did flower jobs on the side. That\xe2\x80\x99s what kept sticking.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cMy grandmother was a florist, so I was able to see her working when I was a child,\xe2\x80\x9d said Maurice. \xe2\x80\x9cI loved watching her create. I ended up having a knack for it, so I started doing flowers, and people responded.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80 
Maurice and his brother Moses opened the cafe in February 2019. There are flower arrangements available, plus fresh flowers throughout the space.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s a place built with a lot of love and a lot of intention. When you feel welcome in a space, it makes you feel better. It makes everything taste better. It gives you a sense of belonging.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80 
The brothers are on a mission to educate their community. Moses, a corporate banker, hosts financial literacy sessions at the cafe. It\xe2\x80\x99s a way to engage the neighborhood in important dialogue around how to save, invest, and budget.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s important for people to see what struggle looks like,\xe2\x80\x9d said Maurice. \xe2\x80\x9cIt\xe2\x80\x99s important to see people that look like you making it, figuring out how to navigate a space that is systematically set up for them to fail. The more we see that, the more we're able to start to even the playing field.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80
Maurice works with @myfriendsplace, an organization helping young people that are experiencing homelessness.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cAs a gay black man, it breaks my heart to see other people of color that don't have the resources needed to have a chance to succeed. My Friend's Place is a rare and beautiful organization doing important work.\xe2\x80\x9d
\xe2\xa0\x80
Visit myfriendsplace.org to learn more.
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x94
\xe2\xa0\x80
Photography by @orianakoren, an LA-based photographer who focuses on documenting black experiences and perspectives."
